Inflation in Europe has cut off on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community statistical office located in Luxembourg was reported.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Contrary to the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the direct interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, with commodity price growth and lower unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "It is necessary to dissuade" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent is a record over the past 12 years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The market share of cereals has increased by 88 per cent and soya prices have also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 percent and, last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will fall from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent but, in 2009, it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month rate of inflation remains around 3 per cent, however, the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the master rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance des Young Democrats) has increased significantly in early December. Thus, since 2002, it has currently had the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Study Institute) has never previously found such low socialist support, 13 per cent.
For the faithful electors, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one fifth (20 percent) for the Hungarian Socialist Party (MSZP).
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Free Democrats Alliance) are below the level of parliamentarians: their support is two percent throughout the population.
On some faithful voters to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared with the earlier low point, the proportion of those who felt that the country's economic situation was particularly serious has never been as high, it has risen to 41 per cent and by 46 per cent additional, the situation is rather serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population is forecast to worsen and only one tenth is forecast to improve the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of the respondents, i.e. a majority never seen in the previous Gallup surveys, found that the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of polls have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister fully and 27 percent to the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of changing political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be treated without a change of government.
While after the riots last October, 35 per cent of the polls hoped that the government and the Prime Minister would remain in office, this rate currently represents only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of intent to vote, 60 per cent of the polls replied that they would certainly vote and 20 per cent additional said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 percent of the polls would certainly participate and 15 percent additional would probably participate. Following the current intentions, the outcome of the referendum would be without doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to registration fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who have expressed their intention to vote at the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital residence costs respectively.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, unlike this year the VAT rate did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Day Economy)
This year, in the budaörs trade triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a significantly higher value than a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
The prices, "who had already flown" in the large food stores last December, have not increased brutally compared to the previous high base.
However, consumers are of course shocked to see that the items purchased clearly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Panier in the tested hypermarkets has exceeded 91 forints, to a minimum, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the level of last year, but the prices of the turkey net, walnut and peacock have greatly increased.
In stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found only from one kilo to 139 forints.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising that, also in this hypermarket, the price of the bottle contained in two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it was only 257 forints of the bottle included.
It does not prevent that this year, in terms of Daily Shopping Cart, Auchan was the cheapest and most expensive Cora.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the daily price of her Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive cart and the cheapest basket this year, we find a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year's lowest and most expensive basket last year is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 on average.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206, while the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noted in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has made trade perplexed, hypermarkets were unable to clearly determine what margin they apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a merchant miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the rate of VAT, the increase in daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was greater than 1,720 forints to the value of the 2006 price, whereas the difference between the least expensive baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the most expensive basket value was more than 1,630 forged than last year's and the prices of the least expensive increased by 1,284 also forged.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we found a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foods, the Institute of Statistics has seen an increase in prices of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily Panier of the latter, this seems almost absurd, since the price level of this product, which was already very expensive last year, has just increased by more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers hold a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in making the price increases brutally accepted by multinationals as well.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they keep recording good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the long-contained food by pallets.
Wednesday morning important tails formed at the three hypermarketed caisses because the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain about not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals make the economy on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overhaul of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also make savings on disinfectants
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the trauma service of the hospital János.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The wounded person in a serious car accident left the hospital but shortly after he had to return there because of an MRSA infection and since then doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Up to 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
It is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacilline resistant gold staphyloccus.
One third of the people are carriers of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
SA infections (such as anginas, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) are very effective for antibiotics, which are easily healing.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which respond well to antibiotics, will develop a bacteria that is resistant to antibiotics that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged functioning of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, on the elderly, small weight or with a weakened organism.
According to the director of the hospital János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital's daily routine.
Above all, you don't have to confuse the infection with the epidemic, you don't find MRSA only the one or you don't look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SA resists antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the caregivers put rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics that are suitable to treat them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling of the sample is not in mode
While the vast majority of MRSA infections may be prevented, current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, Karolina Böröcz says.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases only see the day if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the chief physician of the epidemiology center said.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for healing certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The realization of microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient care and basic care, Karolina Böröcz reported.
Many hospitals make the economy on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA spreads from one patient to another more often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash hands, gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient may not always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in the end of the epidemic, the patients should be removed from each other at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals in difficult financial situations save disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable manner or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenditures for social security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs as well) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
