EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Minister of Hungarian Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed, on Friday, in Budapest, three agreements of a total value of EUR 400 million on a credit line to support education, transport infrastructure and the environment as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, whose credit contract of EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million may be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope first in the framework of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
In the negotiations, the metro line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would recover from the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary had completed the details of the metro financing with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its appropriations according to the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without commitment commission.
