Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication by Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, professional meetings end on Tuesday, but on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the present time, strong discussions are being held on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, they did not wish to discuss accurate figures, but they were prepared to sign an agreement on the reduction by 2020 of greenhouse gas emissions from 25 to 40 per cent compared to the 1990 level.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed, without reducing emissions, to provide financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund established by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by an Executive Board of 16 members probably under the Global Fund for the Environment of the United Nations (GEF), communicated Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its admiral ship role in global efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 by 20 per cent compared to the level reached in 1990, irrespective of the success of the signing of the 2012 Agreement, and was prepared to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if the other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members of that time took the commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The issue is great in Bali, as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be put in place within the two-year period, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, commitments to reduce below the values set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, the necessity of which was highlighted in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which obtained the Nobel Peace Prize, to deal with climate change.
The reduction in emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees of celci would no longer be avoided which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
