The forces of the mega strike gather together
The League trade unions and the National Association of Workers' Councils will, on Friday, constitute their strike commission to coordinate the undetermined strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the Health Fund Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause major traffic jams as rail traffic will be stopped almost entirely and employees of BKV (Common Transport Company) will also be in a hurry until 13 hours.
The Unions of the League will announce, on Friday afternoon, the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Advice.
The LIGA-MOSZ strike commission will also be formed and will serve as the coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, from Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the Health Fund Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Fund Act, trade unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on a follow-up.
According to the Monday agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the Health Fund Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, important stopovers are foreseen in the traffic: railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies will be in danger of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the track will be blocked as well.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, the list of them is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report strike for an indefinite period, others have declared a temporary cessation of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Railway Union (VDSZZZ) have not been able to reach agreement on minimum services, gold, as they approach Christmas parties, more and more are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the beginning of service until 1 p.m., the Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Syndicates of Electricity and Thermal Energy of the League will strike four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Union of Teachers have called for a strike for 2 and 2 hours to 8 hours, respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternately, the Union of Health and Social Sector Employees (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four claims, formulated by the League, requires the Government to withdraw its proposal for health reform and to submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be set up from next year will be introduced in several stages.
The third claim wants a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that would enable the system to pass the functions it deserves before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Railway Union (VDSZSZ), linked to the League's Syndicates, the Ministry of Economy and Transport's proposal on secondary rail lines and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard increased the risk country
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarszágért Mozgalom (Movement for Better Hungary) increases in several aspects the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", the company reports that, in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity, the greatest political risk is that "in the short term, aggressive ethnic clashes can occur as a result of the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the Hungarian and non-Tzigan population."
The research institute has added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Tzigans and the Hungarians."
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened, and the arrival of aggressive conflicts is more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, with increased attention from the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, particularly regarding confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following more publicity given to the reorganisation of the Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 and have been called "national self-defense association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their members to defence missions (castarphs, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, in addition, by referring to the inability of the police, the army, in other words of the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going through the method that, based on the political society and political parties' retaliation, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civil character and association status is therefore only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering these associations in the court but also to constitute a political strategy.
